<SECTION>
<P>
Book Review; Page 6; Book Review Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
1083 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
TOO QUICK FOR KREMLINOLOGY; 
</P>
<P>
GORBACHEV'S RUSSIA BY BASILE KERBLAY TRANSLATED BY RUPERT SWYER (PANTHEON 
BOOKS: $9.95,PAPER; 175 PP.) 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Robert Scheer, Scheer's most recent book is Thinking Tuna Fish, Talking 
Death: Essays on the Pornography of Power (Hill &amp; Wang). 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Change in Gorbachev's Soviet Union has come so rapidly and openly that one can 
only sympathize with the efforts of professional Sovietologists to write books 
that keep pace with events and also say something more interesting than that 
which is available in the mass media. These fellows used to have an easy time 
of it during the old stagnant pre-Gorbachev days when change came sluggishly 
and information was tightly guarded. Then, their tea-leaf reading seemed an 
indispensable exercise. Now, it may be simply beside the point. 
</P>
<P>
This book is an effort to jump on the express of Soviet reform, describe the 
obstacles and predict the ultimate destination, all without pausing for the 
author to catch his breath. The galleys sent out for review were finished in 
June of last year and what with translation and other delays will reach stores 
almost a year later. 
</P>
<P>
Much has happened in the interval to make this brief and hastily thrown 
together book seem dated. For example, the power of Yegor Ligachev, described 
in this book as almost an equal in power to Gorbachev, has declined 
considerably in the last year. By concentrating on breaking events rather than 
on the sources of change, the author has guaranteed his book a short shelf 
life. 
</P>
<P>
The result is not so much a book as a it is a collection of notes for a book. 
Important notes, by an important author, but sketchy and therefore unsatisfying 
nonetheless. 
</P>
<P>
Most interesting is the assertion by Kerblay, a distinguished Sorbonne 
professor, that his fellow Kremlinologists, in evaluating Gorbachev's reforms, 
tend to get it exactly wrong. They ignore the complexity and energy of the mass 
social base of Soviet society and its impact on events. Kerblay chides that 
"Sovietologists generally focus on the political regime or the workings of the 
economy . . . for the well-bred scholar holds that society has no leverage on 
so rigid a system." 
</P>
<P>
He stresses instead the obvious, often missed by the experts, that Gorbachev's 
policies have already profoundly altered the mores of the society on a 
grass-roots level and that uncontrollable and unexpected responses are now 
possible. 
</P>
<P>
Which means that the reform drive no longer fully depends on Gorbachev's 
survival. The genie of freedom, Kerblay seems to argue, is now out of the 
bottle "making a reversion to the status quo ante highly unlikely." 
</P>
<P>
One consequence "is the emergence of public opinion, which is visible in the 
eagerness with which people devour newspapers and follow TV discussions, and 
even more so in the influence that certain movements are coming to exert in 
sensitive areas such as ecology, the preservation of the national heritage, and 
the building of nuclear power stations, to the point where they are starting to 
affect decisions." As proof of his point only last week four Soviet Asian port 
city governments, on their own authority, refused to allow a nuclear-propelled 
container ship to dock. This was an action of municipal independence not likely 
to be tolerated in any Western democracy. 
</P>
<P>
The other basic shift in grass-roots thinking derives from the massive 
condemnation of Stalin that has provoked a far more serious debate on "the 
problem of morality in public life." Meaning that everything that is important 
is up for grabs. 
</P>
<P>
Having established all that, the author inexplicably plunges into a lengthy 
dirge on the ills of Soviet society from alcoholism to the inefficiency of 
agriculture. None of this seems fresh or revealing compared to a typical 
Gorbachev speech. 
</P>
<P>
There is also a lot of other stuff that we know or could easily pick up 
elsewhere: long lists of names, citation of past scandals, and familiar 
biographical detail without point, like Gorbachev's place of birth, education 
and route of ascension to power. It reads like filler intended to pad an 
already too-thin effort. 
</P>
<P>
To make this padding seem portentous, there is the inevitable lapse into 
know-it-all Kremlinology. For example, the assertion that Gorbachev's 
"originality lies less in his ideas, which he borrows frequently from his 
advisers, than in his courage . . . ." Sounds plausible enough, but how does 
the author know this? He doesn't. This sort of statement, authoritative but 
undocumented, just lies there in the text every five pages or so as if ordered 
up by a cynical editor to hold the reader's respect. 
</P>
<P>
Even more offensive is the headlining of the obvious as if it were fresh. A 
chapter on "The Broad Outlines of Gorbachev's Policies," begins with the news 
that "Gorbachev's chief foreign-policy aims are to resume dialogue with the 
United States in order to achieve nuclear arms cuts . . . ." Hot stuff, no? 
</P>
<P>
But tailing the flood of daily news accounts from the Soviet Union is the least 
of this book's problems. More serious is the tendency of its summary thoughts 
to have been called into question by the fast pace of events. 
</P>
<P>
For example, in a discussion on the limits of glasnost, the statement that 
"there never has been any discussion of Soviet foreign policy" in the media was 
disproved in the aftermath of Afghanistan. Or the flat assertion that "the 
Party has no intention of relinquishing either its ideological monopoly or its 
control over all aspects of social life," which, this season, is no longer so 
obvious. 
</P>
<P>
Even the solid passages often tell us what we already know. There is a good 
discussion of the problems inherent in restructuring the Soviet economy, but it 
relies heavily on already published and widely noticed works by Soviet 
economists, led by Abel Aganbegyan. One does not need a Kremlinologist 
interlocutor, as in the old days, to get Aganbegyan's story. The writings of 
this top Gorbachev adviser, who is a frequent American television guest, were 
not smuggled out of his homeland. The man himself is signing them out there in 
the mall. 
</P>
<P>
That is the problem with this thin work. There was a time when a hurried look 
into the Kremlinologists' crystal ball could provide the illusion of insight. 
We were at the mercy of Soviet experts who had access to secret data or who 
were particularly skilled at inferring far too much from a single snapshot of 
the leadership at the Kremlin wall. A book like this one with its dull listing 
of names and events distilled from endless hours of perusing purloined 
documents and reading between the lines of party documents and Pravda accounts 
might have been worth the effort then. But now the latest Gorbachev or Sakharov 
speech or indeed the latest report in The Times will tell us far more. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Book Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA031989-0006 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 32542 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
March 19, 1989, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
