<HEADLINE>
<P>
'MEANING OF ROE VS. WADE' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By complaining of the Los Angeles Police Department's handling of recent 
abortion protests relative to its actions against homeless people and Hispanic 
day laborers, Councilwoman Gloria Molina seems to be assuming some sort of 
political motives on the part of the department (Metro, March 9). I am not an 
official apologist for the department, but as a seven-year veteran I feel 
qualified to comment. 
</P>
<P>
Be they protesters or day laborers, those who block sidewalks and entrances to 
businesses are committing a misdemeanor, a fact which limits our authority to 
take action. Put simply, we can only enforce the laws in these situations after 
a complaint from a victim. In the case of the day laborers, the LAPD responded 
to complaints from merchants and residents who found the day laborers littering 
and urinating on their property. Any citizen has the right to ask the police to 
prevent such activity. 
</P>
<P>
The abortion protesters, however, were seeking a confrontation with the police 
as a means to gain public attention for their cause. The operators of the 
clinics realized this and chose not to have the police intervene and generate 
publicity for the protesters. If they choose to request assistance in the 
future, the LAPD will enforce the laws without regard to the ideology of either 
side. 
</P>
<P>
DANIEL HORAN 
</P>
<P>
Hermosa Beach 
</P>
</TEXT>
