114 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
MEN BY JO MCDOUGALL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
She waits in the car and watches two men 
</P>
<P>
try to sell a truck 
</P>
<P>
to the man who brought her here. 
</P>
<P>
He slams the truck's good door 
</P>
<P>
and lifts the hood. 
</P>
<P>
The men talk, 
</P>
<P>
looking at the ground 
</P>
<P>
as though they were reading something. 
</P>
<P>
She leans back in the car, 
</P>
<P>
glad to be in the company of men. 
</P>
<P>
From "The Woman in the Next Booth" (BkMk Press/UMKC: $8.50, cloth; 60 pp.; 
0-933532-64-4). McDougall, a native of the Arkansas Delta, teaches creative 
writing at Northeast Louisiana University. She was the recipient of the John 
Ciardi Fellowship in Poetry in 1987. This is her first book. Jo McDougall, 
1987. Reprinted by permission of BkMk Press. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
