<HEADLINE>
<P>
 MICRO ... : HAM MAKES EASTER MEAL A SNAP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEAN ANDERSON and ELAINE HANNA, Anderson and Hanna are nutritionists and 
cookbook authors specializing in microwave cookery. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ready-to-eat hams microwave superbly and require very little effort from the 
cook, which makes preparing the traditional Easter meal a snap. 
</P>
<P>
Any kind of commercial ham will do. And you can glaze it or not, as you desire. 
But bear these points in mind. 
</P>
<P>
Trim the ham of all but 1/8 inch of exterior fat. Fat attracts microwaves, 
melts rapidly and produces an abundance of drippings that must be ladled off. 
Further, a heavy coating of fat will cause the lean areas directly underneath 
it to overcook. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Good Spice Choices 
</P>
<P>
If you like, rub a ham with pepper and herbs before it goes into the microwave. 
Sage, thyme, dill weed, crushed caraway or fennel seeds, marjoram and oregano 
are all good choices. 
</P>
<P>
Always use a microwave-safe meat thermometer -- or if your oven has one, a 
temperature probe -- when cooking ham so you can pull it from the oven the 
instant the proper internal temperature is reached. 
</P>
<P>
To keep shank ends and the top edges of hams from drying, shield carefully with 
aluminum foil as the following recipe directs. 
</P>
<P>
GLAZED HAM 
</P>
<P>
1 (4- to 6-pound) bone-in, butt or shank-portion ham or semi-boneless 
ready-to-eat ham or fully cooked, smoked picnic shoulder 
</P>
<P>
1/2 cup light brown sugar, packed 
</P>
<P>
2 tablespoons prepared spicy brown mustard 
</P>
<P>
1 tablespoon cider vinegar 
</P>
<P>
Raisin Sauce, optional 
</P>
<P>
Trim outer layer of fat on ham to 1/8 inch. Tie ham with string (to keep fat 
from separating as ham cooks) and place on microwave-safe rack in shallow 
microwave-safe bake/roast pan. If ham wobbles, prop up with crumpled wax paper. 
</P>
<P>
Smooth sheet of plastic wrap against cut surface of ham, then mold 1- to 2-inch 
foil strip smoothly over upper edge where fat joins lean to deflect microwaves 
and prevent overcooking. (If cooking shank-portion ham, foil-wrap shank end.) 
</P>
<P>
Insert microwave-safe meat thermometer through plastic wrap in center of 
largest muscle not touching fat or bone. Or, use automatic temperature probe 
according to manufacturer's directions. Or, test ham with instant-register 
thermometer as it approaches doneness. 
</P>
<P>
Microwave ham, uncovered, on HIGH (100% power) 5 minutes. Reduce power to 
MEDIUM (50% power) and microwave 7 to 10 minutes per pound. 
</P>
<P>
At half time, invert ham and rotate pan 180 degrees. Remove foil but not 
plastic wrap. Continue microwaving until thermometer registers 130 degrees. If 
desired, score fat, criss-cross fashion, 10 minutes before ham is done. 
</P>
<P>
Drain off all drippings, reserving 1/4 cup for Raisin Sauce. Remove plastic 
wrap. Combine brown sugar, mustard and vinegar and spread over ham. Microwave, 
uncovered, on MEDIUM 5 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
Remove ham from oven, tent with foil and let stand 10 minutes. Serve as is or 
accompany with Raisin Sauce. Makes 6 to 10 servings. 
</P>
<P>
Raisin Sauce 
</P>
<P>
1/4 cup pan dripping (or drippings plus enough bacon drippings to total 1/4 
cup) 
</P>
<P>
1/4 cup flour 
</P>
<P>
2 cups hot water 
</P>
<P>
1/3 cup raisins 
</P>
<P>
1/4 cup medium-dry Madeira, Sherry or Port 
</P>
<P>
Liquid gravy browner, optional 
</P>
<P>
Salt, pepper 
</P>
<P>
Microwave drippings in wax-paper-covered 6-cup measure on HIGH (100% power) 40 
to 50 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
Blend in flour and microwave, uncovered, on HIGH 7 to 10 minutes, stirring 
every 3 minutes, until light brown. Mixture will look grainy but will smooth 
out once liquid is added. 
</P>
<P>
Pour water into drained ham pan and scrap up brown bits. Whisk liquid carefully 
into hot roux being careful of spattering. Microwave, uncovered, on HIGH 3 1/2 
to 4 minutes, whisking at half time, until sauce thickens and boils. 
</P>
<P>
Mix in raisins and Madeira and microwave, uncovered, on MEDIUM-LOW (30% power) 
4 to 5 minutes, until raisins are plump. Mix in gravy browner and salt and 
pepper to taste. Makes 2 1/2 cups. 
</P>
<P>
Note: In ovens of less than 600 watts, increase cooking times about 15%. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA031989-0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 32802 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
March 19, 1989, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Food; Part 10; Page 12; Column 4 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
645 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
 COOK IT LIGHT: A HAM LOAF WITH VEAL -- AND TURKEY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEANNE JONES, Jones is a food consultant and a cookbook author. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DEAR JEANNE: I have used this Ham Loaf recipe since the 1930s. It is hard to 
find veal in small markets, so the last time I made it I used turkey. That 
changed the taste for me very much. I also used liquid egg substitute. 
</P>
<P>
Could you lower the cholesterol and fat, and still have a nice Ham Loaf for me? 
Thank you. 
</P>
<P>
 -- HELEN, Broadlands, Ill. 
</P>
<P>
BAKED HAM LOAF 
</P>
<P>
1 pound ground ham 
</P>
<P>
1 1/2 pounds ground veal 
</P>
<P>
2 eggs, lightly beaten 
</P>
<P>
1 cup cracker crumbs 
</P>
<P>
1 cup milk 
</P>
<P>
1/2 teaspoon salt 
</P>
<P>
1/8 teaspoon black pepper 
</P>
<P>
6 slices pineapple 
</P>
<P>
10 maraschino cherries 
</P>
<P>
3/4 cup brown sugar, packed 
</P>
<P>
1 teaspoon dry mustard 
</P>
<P>
1/4 cup vinegar 
</P>
<P>
Combine ham, veal, eggs, cracker crumbs, milk, salt and pepper. 
</P>
<P>
Generously grease 10 1/2 x 6 1/2-inch loaf pan. Place 6 slices pineapple with 
maraschino cherry in center and between each slice in bottom of pan. Combine 
brown sugar, mustard and vinegar and spread 1/2 over fruit. 
</P>
<P>
Pack meat mixture in pan over fruit and sauce. Spread remaining brown sugar 
mixture over top of loaf. Pack down well. Bake at 400 degrees 1 1/2 to 2 hours. 
Turn out on platter. Makes 6 servings. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR HELEN: This is truly a delicious meat loaf. Unfortunately, there isn't 
much I can do to it that is going to make it significantly healthier than the 
variations you may have already tried. 
</P>
<P>
Veal is naturally higher in cholesterol than almost any other meat. Since the 
turkey substitution didn't taste right to you, I have left the veal alone. Just 
be sure you use the leanest meats that you can get. You might try using turkey 
and veal in combination (such as 1 pound veal and 1/2 pound turkey). Turkey has 
about half the cholesterol of veal, and only about two-thirds of the calories. 
</P>
<P>
I have used liquid egg substitute and non-fat milk in my revision, and I also 
specified pineapple packed in juice to be sure you aren't using the kind packed 
in heavy syrup, which is practically pure sugar. I don't recommend using 
maraschino cherries either, so I made them optional. I prefer to avoid the 
chemical additives they contain, especially the red dye. 
</P>
<P>
By eliminating the salt and substituting whole-wheat bread crumbs for the 
cracker crumbs, I was able to reduce the sodium in your recipe. I like the 
flavor the bread crumbs give the loaf as well as the added fiber. 
</P>
<P>
The sauce is another source of calories, so I reduced the amount of brown sugar 
and specified "dark brown sugar" to get maximum flavor for the calories 
consumed. I also based my nutritional analysis on both recipes making eight 
servings since I determined that the whole loaf yields about sixteen 1/2-inch 
slices. 
</P>
<P>
You have been enjoying this Ham Loaf for more than 50 years, and I hope my 
revised version will enable you to enjoy it for another 50! 
</P>
<P>
REVISED BAKED HAM LOAF 
</P>
<P>
1 pound extra-lean baked ham, ground or very finely chopped 
</P>
<P>
1 1/2 pounds extra-lean ground veal 
</P>
<P>
1/2 cup liquid egg substitute 
</P>
<P>
1 cup nonfat milk 
</P>
<P>
1 cup soft whole-wheat bread crumbs 
</P>
<P>
1/8 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper 
</P>
<P>
1/2 cup dark brown sugar, packed 
</P>
<P>
1 teaspoon dry mustard 
</P>
<P>
1/4 cup white vinegar 
</P>
<P>
6 slices canned pineapple, packed in juice 
</P>
<P>
10 maraschino cherries, optional 
</P>
<P>
Combine ham, veal, egg substitute, milk, bread crumbs and pepper. Combine brown 
sugar, dry mustard and vinegar in separate bowl. 
</P>
<P>
Spray 10 1/2 x 6 1/2-inch loaf pan with non-stick vegetable coating. Place 6 
slices pineapple on bottom of pan. Place cherry in center of -- and in between 
-- pineapple slices. Pour 1/2 sauce mixture over fruit. 
</P>
<P>
Pack meat mixture in pan over fruit and sauce. Pour remaining sauce over top of 
loaf. Bake at 400 degrees 1 1/2 to 2 hours. Turn out onto platter. Makes 8 
servings, or 16 (1/2-inch) slices. 
</P>
<P>
Each serving contains approximately: 
</P>
<P>
Original Recipe: 
</P>
<P>
Calories: 420 
</P>
<P>
Cholesterol: 165 mg 
</P>
<P>
Fat: 17 gm 
</P>
<P>
Sodium: 982 mg 
</P>
<P>
Revised Recipe: 
</P>
<P>
Calories: 338 
</P>
<P>
Cholesterol: 83 mg 
</P>
<P>
Fat: 11 gm 
</P>
<P>
Sodium: 840 mg 
</P>
</TEXT>
