<HEADLINE>
<P>
 FOOD AND COMMON SENSE: SORRY SAGA OF EFFECTS OF ALCOHOL ON PREGNANCY AND 
UNBORN INFANTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DR. JEAN MAYER and JEANNE GOLDBERG 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Question: I recently read an article advising against drinking alcohol during 
pregnancy. The author said that the dangers of alcohol were first identified in 
a report published only 20 years ago. Is that true? 
</P>
<P>
Answer: Not exactly, although the modern process for studying the problem fell 
into place around then. An issue of the journal Public Health Reports devoted 
to alcohol-related problems contains an article by Dr. Kenneth R. Warren of the 
National Institute of Alcohol Abuse and Alcoholism and Richard Bast of the 
National Clearinghouse for Alcoholism and Drug Information that reviews the 
sorry saga of concern about the effects of alcohol on unborn infants. 
</P>
<P>
Lower birth weights and a rise in deaths were observed during the London "Gin 
Epidemic" between 1720 and 1750. It was a period of good wages, plentiful food 
and relative freedom from epidemic diseases. However, Parliament had reduced 
controls on the distilling and sale of gin in order to support the gentry who 
furnished the raw materials. This encouraged alcohol consumption. Reports and 
petitions from physicians and others referred to effects on children that 
correlate with what we today call Fetal Alcohol Syndrome (FAS). 
</P>
<P>
Such reports on the impact of alcohol on growth and development continued 
through the 18th and 19th centuries, often mixing science and mortality. In 
1899, Dr. William Sullivan reported his observations of 600 offspring of 120 
women alcoholic prisoners in Liverpool, describing what was later called FAS. 
</P>
<P>
Here in the United States (as well as Great Britain), with the arrival of 
Prohibition, concern about the effects of alcohol on pregnancy were largely 
ignored for about 20 years. Ironically, much of the research conducted during 
the 1940s and beyond tended to refute the harmful ramifications of drinking. 
Alcohol was even recommended to pregnant women for "sluggish digestion" and was 
used to delay labor. 
</P>
<P>
Then in 1967, Alexandre Lamache, a family physician in Rennes, France, 
presented to the French Academy his observations of 1,245 children, collected 
during 37 years of practice. This signaled a rebirth of interest in 
alcohol-related birth abnormalities. A year later, a group of French 
researchers published what was apparently the first well-organized study of 
birth defects. In 1970, the pattern of characteristic abnormalities labeled FAS 
was first described in this country. 
</P>
<P>
Sadly, estimates based on 20 studies from Australia, Europe and North America 
indicate that Fetal Alcohol Syndrome is the leading cause of mental 
retardation, ahead of Down's syndrome and spina bifida. 
</P>
<P>
Q: Please tell me something about the vegetable called kohlrabi. 
</P>
<P>
A: Botanically, kohlrabi (the name derives from the German word for cabbage and 
the Latin word for turnip) belongs to the cabbage family. Although the leaves 
are edible, the turnip-like root is usually considered the best part. 
</P>
<P>
Nutritionally, a half cup cooked contains about 40 calories and provides some B 
vitamins and Vitamin C. It is an excellent source of potassium, a useful 
vegetable for people taking diuretics that cause them to lose that nutrient. 
</P>
<P>
While it can be easily diced and cooked until tender, it can also be braised in 
broth, whipped with potatoes, served with sauces, stuffed, cooked in soup, or 
served cold with vinaigrette dressing. Introduced in China from Europe during 
the 7th Century, it appears in various Chinese recipes. 
</P>
<P>
Q: I've noticed that when nutrients are added to foods, the word "enriched" 
sometimes appears on the label, while other times the word "fortified" is used. 
What, if any, is the difference? 
</P>
<P>
A: Both terms are associated with the addition of nutrients, but the underlying 
concepts differ. "Enrichment" refers to the restoration of nutrients discarded 
during processing. Nutrients are added back at levels equal to or not much 
greater than those in the original food. The classic example of enrichment is 
the restoration of iron along with the B vitamins thiamine, riboflavin and 
niacin to white flour. 
</P>
<P>
"Fortification" is the addition of nutrients that either are not normally 
present in food, or the amount available is too small to be nutritionally 
significant. A number of fortification measures have been dramatically 
effective in combatting major nutritional deficiencies. 
</P>
<P>
For example, more than 40 years ago, carotene, which the body converts to 
Vitamin A, was first added to margarine in Denmark when it was discovered that 
the switch from butter to margarine during World War II was linked to blindness 
among children there. Similarly, milk was a logical vehicle for Vitamin D 
fortification to prevent rickets. And the addition of iodine to salt was an 
effective tool in preventing goiter. 
</P>
<P>
Those were important public-health measures. In recent years, the basis for 
much fortification seems far less clear. In many cases, the addition of 
generous helpings of vitamins and minerals appears to be inspired more by the 
goal of selling products than by a demonstrated need for the added nutrients. 
Selecting heavily fortified cereals or other foods containing as much as 100% 
of the U.S. Recommended Daily Allowance for some nutrients is no substitute for 
consuming a varied and well-balanced diet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
