<HEADLINE>
<P>
CREATIVE COMPROMISE IS ELUSIVE FOR ARTISTS, SPONSORS; 
</P>
<P>
BOTH SIDES STUMBLE IN SEARCH FOR WORK THAT IS A BIT 'OUT THERE' -- BUT NOT TOO 
FAR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALLAN JALON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
While many artists are dropping out of performance, others have tried to adapt 
to the pressures of playing to a more conventional audience. The compromise can 
be painful. 
</P>
<P>
"They want to make a living at it, but that's never what performance was about 
before," said RoseLee Goldberg, who teaches performance art history at New York 
University. "The artists find themselves trying to walk a tightrope between the 
avant-garde and the establishment, and that is very difficult." 
</P>
<P>
John White, a Venice artist who is also a UC Irvine guest lecturer on 
performance, had an encounter with the Los Angeles Music Center last summer 
that underscored the risks of creative compromise, both for artists and for 
mainstream sponsors in search of art that is a little "out there." 
</P>
<P>
For 20 years, White performed pieces that entwined aspects of visual art and 
storytelling. He worked in storefronts, private homes, hospitals and schools, 
rarely pocketing more that $300 a shot. He once hit a golf ball out of a 
fourth-story window while blindfolded, as a concealed audiotape congratulated 
him on the shot. 
</P>
<P>
Discouraged by the sand-trap economics of performance, White quit 2 years ago 
to focus on painting. But in 1987, when the Music Center invited proposals for 
a piece for L.A. Alive Festival, White decided to give it one more swing, as a 
director this time. He won the commission. 
</P>
<P>
"The Music Center!" he declared. "Performance was going uptown, and I wanted to 
see what that was like. For years, one of my big things has been to get 
performance into venues where it had never played before. And they were 
offering $2,000!" 
</P>
<P>
He devised a light-heartedly funky, Californian spin on Dadaism: He had the 
Shrimps -- an L.A.-based performance art/theatrical troupe, noted in part for 
their big, wide or elongated bodies -- dress in tropical Hawaiian outfits and 
throw around tires, crates, ladders and other junkyard items -- all painted 
black. 
</P>
<P>
Two days before show time, he received a phone call. Esther Wachtell, the Music 
Center's president, had about 10 complaints from people who had seen White's 
work in rehearsal on the outdoor plaza. 
</P>
<P>
"People were eating their lunch, and they were from senior citizens' housing 
and apartments nearby," Wachtell said. "They were watching him rehearse and 
were offended by the anger that seemed to underlay a lot of his presentation." 
</P>
<P>
Wachtell asked Music Center volunteer Jennifer Diener to ask White to shorten 
his piece and use "a little less volatile flinging around." 
</P>
<P>
Diener said she passed on those complaints and one other, about the Shrimps. 
White said he will always remember her remark: "Those peoples' bodies aren't 
the sorts of bodies we want associated with the image of the Los Angeles Music 
Center." 
</P>
<P>
Attempting a cure-all concession that still poked fun at what he perceived as 
the Music Center's stuffy self-regard, White dressed his performers in tuxedos. 
But he said he has not regained his sense of humor about the episode. 
</P>
<P>
Now he believes that he is back to painting for good: "Having control over what 
I do is my only power as an artist. Taking that away from people will be the 
death of performance." ALLAN JALON 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Instructors and students in a performance art class at UC Irvine watch 
Carolyn Lane's multimedia production. 'Having control over what I do is my only 
power as an artist.' ; Photo, -- John White: UC Irvine guest lecturer DAVID 
MURONAKA / L.A. Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
